# Deferred work

- Remove the guest VLAN dual-stack (IPv4) once Windows CLAT ships in stable:
  repo side per the guest_ipv4 comment in host_vars/vanguard.yml, then on
  vanguard:
    delete interfaces ethernet eth2 vif 50 address 10.0.50.1/24
    delete service dhcp-server shared-network-name guest
    delete nat source rule 1000
    delete firewall ipv4 input filter rule 1000
    delete firewall ipv4 input filter rule 1001
    delete firewall ipv4 forward filter rule 1000

- Create the untrusted VLAN (60) in the gateway role: internet only, no
  inter-VLAN access; intra-VLAN isolation via Proxmox per-VM firewall (and
  switch port isolation once lagrange exists)
- Deploy atlas (step-ca) and distribute its root certificate to every managed
  device

- NTP redirect rule: force IoT devices with hardcoded public NTP (pool.ntp.org)
  to use vanguard instead (outbound UDP 123 redirect)
- Tighten firewall forward rule 310 (services -> iot) to gaia's address once
  gaia exists
- Once polaris serves encrypted DNS, switch firewall forward rule 215
  (trusted -> polaris) from plaintext 53 to the TLS port (853 DoT / 443 DoH)
  and drop plaintext
- Lock down pioneer (label printer) to only the protocols it actually needs:
  restrict trusted -> pioneer to its print ports (e.g. IPP 631, raw 9100) and
  drop everything else, once the device is on the network and its real port
  usage is confirmed
- mDNS repeater between services and iot if a device needs auto-discovery
- Remove default-log from the input chain once the network is stable (keep it
  on forward)
- Configure eth1 (5G backup WAN) and WAN failover
- Managed switch: VLAN enforcement + untagged wired devices (currently wired
  devices must tag their own traffic)
- Once polaris is built: do DNS64 locally (AdGuard), point RDNSS at polaris,
  and restore Cloudflare + Google as plain upstreams
- Split DNS into layers so we can serve record types AdGuard can't (TXT/SRV/CAA
  — AdGuard only does A/AAAA/CNAME rewrites). Proposed flow: clients -> polaris
  (AdGuard: filter + per-client logging) -> a resolver authoritative for .x (any
  record type, from a typed zone in the repo) that also does DNS64 and forwards
  public queries to Google; polaris stops doing DNS64 / .x rewrites. Runs on the
  dns VM on a non-53 port with AdGuard's upstream pointed at it. Also unlocks
  ACME DNS-01 / wildcard certs later. Software undecided: PowerDNS (Route-53-
  style, API-first, auth+recursor split — AWS structures Route 53 the same way),
  BIND9 (all-in-one), or Knot (modern, split).
- Once the API DNS (above) exists, switch harmony's ACME from TLS-ALPN-01 to
  DNS-01 and delete the per-domain `genesis` network aliases on the harmony
  container. Those aliases are a workaround: TLS-ALPN-01/HTTP-01 require atlas to
  connect to the service domain to validate, which hairpins because atlas and
  harmony are both containers — so each routed domain is aliased onto genesis to
  make that hop container-to-container. DNS-01 (TXT record, no inbound
  connection) removes the hop and the aliases entirely.
- Ship vanguard logs to hubble via remote syslog (Grafana + Loki + Alloy) and
  add the management -> services syslog firewall rule
- Consider restricting the forward ICMPv6 rule to specific types (currently
  allows ping between all VLANs)
- Replace the Proxmox API self-signed cert with an atlas-issued one and drop
  `insecure = true` from terraform/providers.tf once atlas exists
- Scope the Terraform Proxmox token to a dedicated terraform@pve user with a
  minimal custom role (privsep 1 + ACLs) instead of the root@pam privsep-0 token
- Docker Compose service hygiene: audit every existing role so each service
  meets the "Service definition hygiene" requirement in CLAUDE.md.

- Migrate unity from the standalone UniFi Network Application (the Docker image)
  to UniFi OS Server: Ubiquiti is deprecating the standalone app ("won't support
  upcoming Network versions"). UniFi OS Server is a full OS appliance, not a
  container — so it becomes a dedicated Terraform-provisioned VM, not an Ansible
  Docker role, and is more Ubiquiti-account/cloud-coupled. Do it when committing
  to the UniFi switch/AP buildout or when the standalone app stops getting
  updates; until then the Docker app works and fits the repo.
